fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:
\begin {align*}
  \phi _t(z) &= \mathbb {P}(x_{0}, \ldots , x_t, z) \\
  &= \mathbb {P}(x_0, \ldots , x_t \mid  z) \mathbb {P}(z) \\
  &= \mathbb {P}(x_0, \ldots , x_{t - 1} \mid  x_t, z) \mathbb {P}(x_t \mid  z) \mathbb {P}(z)
.\end {align*}
Since this is a HMM, (x_{0}, \ldots , x_{t - 1}) \perp  x_{t} \mid  z_{t}. Therefore, we can drop the x_t from the first term, such that
\begin {align*}
  \phi _t(z) &= \mathbb {P}(x_0, \ldots , x_{t - 1} \mid  z) \mathbb {P}(x_t \mid  z) \mathbb {P}(z) \\
  &= \mathbb {P}(x_0, \ldots , x_{t - 1}, z) \mathbb {P}(x_t \mid  z) \\
  &= \mathbb {P}(x_t \mid  z) \sum _{z'} \mathbb {P}(x_0, \ldots , x_{t - 1}, z', z)  \\
  &= \mathbb {P}(x_t \mid  z) \sum _{z'} \mathbb {P}(x_0, \ldots , x_{t - 1} \mid  z', z) \mathbb {P}(z \mid  z') \mathbb {P}(z')
.\end {align*}
Similarly, (x_{0}, \ldots , x_{t - 1}) \perp  z_{t} \mid  z_{t - 1}, such that
\begin {align*}
   \phi _t(z) &= \mathbb {P}(x_t \mid  z) \sum _{z'} \mathbb {P}(x_0, \ldots , x_{t - 1} \mid  z') \mathbb {P}(z \mid  z') \mathbb {P}(z') \\
&= \mathbb {P}(x_t \mid  z) \sum _{z'} \mathbb {P}(x_0, \ldots , x_{t - 1}, z') \mathbb {P}(z \mid  z') \\
&= \mathbb {P}(x_t \mid  z) \sum _{z'} \phi _{t - 1}(z') \mathbb {P}(z \mid  z')
.\end {align*}

Here z' ranges over the possible values of z_{t - 1}. We see that \phi _t(z) depends only on information from time t and t - 1. Therefore, information propagates forward in time.

\begin {align*}
  \beta _t(z) &= \mathbb {P}(x_{t + 1}, \ldots , x_{T} \mid  z) \\
  &= \sum _{z'} \mathbb {P}(x_{t + 1}, \ldots , x_{T}, z' \mid  z) \\
  &= \sum _{z'} \mathbb {P}(x_{t + 2}, \ldots , x_{T} \mid  x_{t + 1}, z', z) \mathbb {P}(x_{t + 1} \mid  z', z) \mathbb {P}(z' \mid  z)
.\end {align*}
First, since this is a HMM, everything is independent of z_{t} given z_{t + 1}. Therefore, we can simplify
\begin {align*}
  \beta _t(z) &= \sum _{z'} \mathbb {P}(x_{t + 2}, \ldots , x_{T} \mid  x_{t + 1}, z') \mathbb {P}(x_{t + 1} \mid  z') \mathbb {P}(z' \mid  z).
\end {align*}
Additionally, (x_{t + 2}, \ldots , x_{T}) \perp  x_{t + 1} \mid  z_{t + 1}, such that
\begin {align*}
  \beta _t(z) &= \sum _{z'} \mathbb {P}(x_{t + 2}, \ldots , x_{T} \mid  z') \mathbb {P}(x_{t + 1} \mid  z') \mathbb {P}(z' \mid  z) \\
&= \sum _{z'} \beta _{t + 1}(z') \mathbb {P}(x_{t + 1} \mid  z') \mathbb {P}(z' \mid  z)
.\end {align*}

Here z' ranges over the possible values of z_{t + 1}. We see that \beta _t(z) depends only on information from time t and t + 1. Therefore, information propagates backward in time.

